  "analysis_markdown": "## Local Diff Analysis\n\n**Partial timeout fix with critical gaps** — Increased `CoderConfig.session_timeout` default from 600s to 3600s (10-minute to 1-hour) to address premature task timeouts during agent execution. Changes include updating the Pydantic model default in `factory/models.py` and removing explicit `session_timeout=600` override from inline task creation in `factory/cli.py`. However, the fix is **incomplete**: two critical timeout fallback locations (`factory/poller.py:65` and `factory/session.py:191`) were not updated, leaving them hardcoded to the old 600s default. This creates silent timeout mismatches for GitHub issue polling and any future code paths that call `wait_for_status()` without explicit timeout arguments. The diff also lacks test coverage, per-task configurability, and documentation of the 6x increase rationale or compounding timeout effects across multiple phases (coder + eval + crucible + evaluator can total 77+ minutes per iteration).\n\n### Suggested Review Focus\n- Timeout consistency across code paths: Three separate locations maintain independent timeout defaults: (1) `CoderConfig.session_timeout` (updated to 3600), (2) `poller.py:65` fallback (still 600 — not fixed), (3) `session.py:191` function default (still 600 — not fixed). This violates DRY and creates maintenance hazards where future code paths silently revert to the old 10-minute timeout instead of the intended 1 hour, defeating the fix's purpose.\n- Incomplete round-2 implementation: Round 1 Crucible review explicitly identified 4 critical/warning findings requiring 4 synchronized changes. The diff addresses only 2 of 4: `models.py` and `cli.py` were updated, but `poller.py` and `session.py` remain unaddressed. This is a failure to implement the complete fix identified by automated review.\n- Compounding timeout impact documentation: Each coder iteration now takes 3600s, and with `max_iterations=3`, eval (300s), crucible (600s), and evaluator (120s) per iteration, total runtime could reach 4600s per iteration or 13,800s total. No documentation explains this compounding effect or validates that actual workloads fit within these boundaries.\n- Test coverage and edge case handling: Timeout logic is mission-critical (controls task success/failure) but has zero unit/integration tests. Three separate timeout defaults mean three edge cases: (1) `wait_for_status()` called without explicit timeout, (2) `poller.issue_to_task()` with no coder template, (3) concurrent 3600s sessions on worker. Manual end-to-end testing per CLAUDE.md is insufficient for a 6x timeout multiplier.\n- Implicit default behavior and auditability: Removed explicit `session_timeout=600` from `_build_inline_task()` makes the timeout value implicit and harder to discover during code review. No CLI flag (`--session-timeout`) exists to override timeout per task, reducing runtime flexibility and making it difficult to experiment with optimal values.\n\n### Trade-offs\n- **Prevents premature timeouts but increases latency for stuck agents** — 6x timeout increase avoids timeout failures but masks genuinely hung tasks longer. Requires external monitoring to distinguish legitimate slow execution from deadlocks.\n- **Worker resources held 6x longer per iteration** — Longer-lived tmux sessions, SSH connections, and disk/memory footprint multiply resource contention. Requires validation that worker has capacity and cleanup mechanisms for sustained 3600s+ sessions.\n- **Single-source-of-truth violation** — Removed explicit timeout from CLI to avoid duplication, but now depends on class default in `models.py` which could drift in future refactors. Two other hardcoded defaults remain orphaned.\n- **No per-task configurability** — All tasks get 3600s regardless of complexity; simple tasks over-provisioned, complex tasks potentially still under-provisioned. No data-driven justification for 3600s threshold.\n- **Deferred validation — runtime metrics not collected** — 6x increase justified by anecdotal timeout failures but no baseline metrics on typical coder execution times, eval durations, or worker resource capacity under sustained load.\n\n### Affected Modules\n- `factory/models.py` — `CoderConfig.session_timeout` default changed from 600 to 3600; comment lacks rationale documentation\n- `factory/cli.py` — `_build_inline_task()` removed hardcoded `session_timeout=600` override; now relies on implicit model default\n- `factory/poller.py` — `issue_to_task()` line 65 still has hardcoded fallback of 600s when `template.coder is None` (**NOT FIXED**)\n- `factory/session.py` — `wait_for_status()` line 191 still has default parameter `timeout=600` (**NOT FIXED**)\n- `factory/runner.py` — Polling loop uses `task.coder.session_timeout` but no validation that workloads fit within 3600s-per-iteration bounds\n- `factory/evaluator.py` — Likely inherits timeout behavior; unclear if evaluator phase respects CoderConfig timeout or has independent limit\n\n### Call Chain\n- **cli.py:**`_build_inline_task()` → creates `TaskDefinition` with `CoderConfig(prompt=..., max_iterations=3, agents=[...])` → uses implicit `session_timeout=3600` default\n- **poller.py:**`issue_to_task()` → creates `CoderConfig(session_timeout=template.coder.session_timeout if template.coder else 600)` → **silently uses 600s for GitHub issue tasks without explicit coder template**\n- **runner.py:**`run_task(task)` → extracts `task.coder.session_timeout` (3600) → passes to `session.wait_for_status(..., timeout=task.coder.session_timeout)`\n- **session.py:**`wait_for_status(..., timeout=task.coder.session_timeout)` → explicitly passes 3600, but function signature still has default `timeout=600` which would revert if caller omits argument\n- **runner.py:**`wait_for_status()` returns 'timeout' → sets `run.state = RunState.failed`, logs `f'Coder timed out after {task.coder.session_timeout}s'`\n\n### Design Patterns\n- **Pydantic config object with class defaults** — `CoderConfig` centralizes timeout configuration as a single source of truth (intended design), but implementation violates this by maintaining two other hardcoded defaults (`poller.py:65` and `session.py:191`)\n- **Default-over-explicit pattern** — Removed hardcoded `session_timeout=600` from CLI to reduce duplication and rely on class default, but increases implicit behavior and reduces discoverability during code review\n- **Config inheritance/propagation** — `CoderConfig.session_timeout` should flow uniformly to all execution paths (`cli.py`, `poller.py`, `runner.py`, `session.py`), but incomplete synchronization leaves orphaned defaults\n- **Timeout parameter with fallback** — `poller.py:65` uses ternary fallback `if template.coder else 600`, but fallback was not updated when class default changed (anti-pattern: hardcoded fallback instead of relying on Pydantic default)\n- **Optional parameter with default** — `session.py:191` `wait_for_status(timeout: int = 600)` makes timeout optional, which creates a maintenance footgun where future code can silently use wrong timeout\n\n### Reviewer Checklist\n- ❌ **Critical:** Verify that `factory/poller.py:65` fallback has been updated from `else 600` to `else 3600` to match new CoderConfig default. Search diff for `poller.py` — it should NOT be in the 'unchanged files' section.\n- ❌ **Critical:** Verify that `factory/session.py:191` has synchronized the `wait_for_status()` default parameter. Either: (a) changed from `timeout: int = 600` to `timeout: int` (no default, requires explicit caller), or (b) changed to `timeout: int = 3600`. Option (a) is safer; grep for all `wait_for_status()` callers to confirm they all pass explicit timeout.\n- ⚠️ **Warning:** Confirm that no other hardcoded `timeout=600` or timeout-related fallback values exist in the codebase. Run: `grep -rn 'timeout.*600' factory/` to find orphaned defaults.\n- ⚠️ **Warning:** Verify `factory/evaluator.py` timeout behavior — does evaluator phase inherit from `CoderConfig.session_timeout` or have independent timeout? Document in commit message.\n- ℹ️ **Info:** Check if commit message or code comments document: (a) why 3600s was chosen, (b) typical coder execution times for target workloads, (c) per-iteration max runtime calculation (3600 + eval + crucible + evaluator = ~4620s), (d) trade-offs of longer timeout (resource cost, failure detection latency).\n- ℹ️ **Info:** Verify worker capacity and cleanup: With `max_iterations=3` and 3600s per iteration, a single run can hold tmux session/SSH connection for 10,800s. With concurrent runs, resource pressure multiplies. Confirm worker has cleanup guarantees for timed-out sessions.\n- ℹ️ **Info:** If this is a partial/WIP fix, confirm that follow-up commits will address `poller.py` and `session.py` in the next round. If not, **block this PR** — incomplete timeout synchronization defeats the purpose.\n- 📝 **Testing:** Confirm whether test coverage exists for timeout edge cases: (1) `wait_for_status()` with explicit vs. default timeout, (2) `issue_to_task()` timeout without coder template, (3) timeout state transition to `RunState.failed`, (4) session cleanup after timeout. If not, request tests before merge.\n- 🔍 **Design Review:** Confirm whether `--session-timeout` CLI flag should be added for per-task configurability. Current design (implicit default only) reduces flexibility for experimenting with optimal timeouts.\n- 📊 **Metrics:** Confirm whether runtime profiling data for typical coder/eval/crucible/evaluator phases has been collected to validate that 3600s is data-driven vs. arbitrary. If not, document assumption and commit to collecting metrics post-merge.\n",
