  "pr_comment_markdown": "## Crucible Review Summary\n\n- Issues: 17\n- Critical: 7, Warning: 6\n\n### Top Actions\n- [Critical] Incomplete implementation: Round 1 Critical findings not addressed (<unknown>)\n- [Critical] Incomplete implementation: Round 1 Critical findings not fully addressed (<unknown>)\n- [Critical] Missing documentation of timeout increase rationale (factory/models.py:44)\n- [Critical] Missing rationale documentation for 6x timeout increase (600s→3600s) (factory/models.py:44)\n- [Critical] Timeout fallback value not synchronized with CoderConfig default (factory/poller.py:65)\n- [Critical] Incomplete timeout default parameter synchronization (factory/session.py:191)\n- [Critical] Unsafe default timeout parameter in wait_for_status() signature (factory/session.py:191)\n- [Warning] Zero test coverage for critical timeout behavior (<unknown>)\n- [Warning] Zero test coverage for timeout behavior and edge cases (<unknown>)\n- [Warning] Zero test coverage for critical timeout behavior and edge cases (<unknown>)\n- [Warning] Removed explicit timeout makes behavior implicit and reduces auditability (factory/cli.py:133)\n- [Warning] Implicit timeout behavior in inline task creation reduces auditability (factory/cli.py:133)\n- [Warning] Compounding timeout effect not documented or validated (factory/runner.py:210)\n\n### Notable Issues\n- **Incomplete implementation: Round 1 Critical findings not addressed** `<unknown>`: Round 1 review explicitly identified FOUR critical/warning timeout synchronization issues requiring fixes in four separate locations: (1) `models.py:44` — CoderConfig default (FIXED in this diff), (2) `cli.py:133` — remove hardcoded override (FIXED in this diff), (3) `poller.py:65` — update fallback (NOT FIXED — remains hardcoded at 600), (4) `session.py:191` — synchronize default parameter (NOT FIXED — remains at 600). The round-2 commit addresses only 2 of 4 required fixes, leaving the timeout configuration inconsistent across three separate code paths. This is a **failure to implement the complete fix** identified by automated review and represents a correctness regression.\n- **Incomplete implementation: Round 1 Critical findings not fully addressed** `<unknown>`: Round 1 review identified FOUR critical/warning synchronization issues requiring fixes in separate locations: (1) models.py:44 CoderConfig default—FIXED, (2) cli.py:133 remove hardcoded override—FIXED, (3) poller.py:65 update fallback—NOT FIXED (remains 600), (4) session.py:191 remove default parameter—NOT FIXED (remains 3600). This commit addresses only 2 of 4 required fixes, leaving timeout configuration inconsistent across code paths and defeating the fix's purpose. Two Critical-severity findings remain unresolved, creating correctness hazards.\n- **Missing documentation of timeout increase rationale** `factory/models.py:44`: The session_timeout default was increased 6x from 600s to 3600s (1 hour), but the code provides no explanation for why this value was chosen, what workloads require 1 hour, or what metrics/profiling justified this threshold. The comment at line 44 reads only '# seconds to wait for the agent to finish per iteration' with no context about the increase, trade-offs, or decision rationale. This makes it difficult for code reviewers, maintainers, and future developers to assess whether 3600s is appropriate or understand when to revisit this threshold.\n- **Missing rationale documentation for 6x timeout increase (600s→3600s)** `factory/models.py:44`: The session_timeout default was increased from 600s to 3600s (1 hour) without documenting the decision rationale, target workloads, or metrics that justified this change. Current comment only states '# seconds to wait for the agent to finish per iteration' with no context. Additionally, compounding timeout effects across phases are not documented: coder (3600s) + eval (300s) + crucible (600s) + evaluator (120s) = ~4620s per iteration; with max_iterations=3 = ~13,860s (3.8 hours) total per run. This makes it difficult for reviewers and maintainers to assess appropriateness or understand when to revisit the threshold.\n- **Timeout fallback value not synchronized with CoderConfig default** `factory/poller.py:65`: The issue_to_task() function hardcodes session_timeout=600 as fallback when template.coder is None (line 65), but CoderConfig default was increased to 3600s. This creates silent timeout mismatch: normal runs get 3600s from CoderConfig default, but runs without coder template get only 600s from this fallback—silently reverting to the old problematic timeout. This is the type of inconsistency that caused the original issue.\n- **Incomplete timeout default parameter synchronization** `factory/session.py:191`: The wait_for_status() function signature still defines timeout=3600 as a default parameter (line 191). While this is safer than the old 600, the Crucible review correctly identifies that the safest approach is to remove the default entirely. The current single caller (runner.py:253) explicitly passes timeout=task.coder.session_timeout, so the default is not currently used. However, this creates a maintenance hazard: future code that calls wait_for_status() without an explicit timeout parameter will silently revert to 3600s instead of whatever timeout the caller intended to use. This violates DRY and the single-source-of-truth principle.\n- **Unsafe default timeout parameter in wait_for_status() signature** `factory/session.py:191`: The wait_for_status() function signature still defines timeout=3600 as a default parameter (line 191). While safer than the old 600s, the safest approach is to remove the default entirely. The only current caller (runner.py:253) explicitly passes timeout=task.coder.session_timeout. Leaving the default creates a maintenance hazard: future calls without explicit timeout will silently revert to 3600s instead of using the caller's intended timeout, violating DRY and risking silent timeout mismatches.\n- **Zero test coverage for critical timeout behavior** `<unknown>`: This commit changes timeout behavior across multiple mission-critical code paths (timeout detection at runner.py:290-298, RunState transition, session lifecycle management) but adds ZERO unit or integration tests. Per CLAUDE.md, 'No tests exist yet — the main way to verify changes is running a task end-to-end,' which is grossly insufficient for a 6x timeout multiplier change affecting core control flow. Untested edge cases include: (1) `wait_for_status()` called without explicit timeout (uses default), (2) `poller.issue_to_task()` without coder template (uses fallback), (3) concurrent 3600s+ sessions on worker (resource impact), (4) timeout state transition to RunState.failed and logging, (5) tmux session cleanup after timeout. Without tests, future refactoring risks silently re-introducing timeout mismatches.\n- **Zero test coverage for timeout behavior and edge cases** `<unknown>`: Per CLAUDE.md: 'No tests exist yet — the main way to verify changes is running a task end-to-end.' This timeout change affects mission-critical control flow (timeout detection, RunState transitions, session cleanup) but includes zero unit or integration tests. Critical untested edge cases: (1) wait_for_status() behavior with explicit vs. default timeout, (2) poller.issue_to_task() timeout handling with/without template.coder, (3) CoderConfig instantiation always yields session_timeout=3600, (4) timeout state transition to RunState.failed, (5) session cleanup after timeout (tmux kill, port release). Without tests, future refactoring risks silently re-introducing 600s timeouts in edge paths.\n- **Zero test coverage for critical timeout behavior and edge cases** `<unknown>`: This 6x timeout multiplier change affects mission-critical control flow (timeout detection at runner.py:290-298, RunState transitions, session cleanup) but includes zero unit or integration tests. Per CLAUDE.md: 'No tests exist yet—the main way to verify changes is running a task end-to-end,' which is insufficient for control flow changes of this magnitude. Untested edge cases: (1) wait_for_status() with explicit vs. implicit timeout, (2) issue_to_task() with/without template.coder, (3) CoderConfig instantiation always yields 3600, (4) timeout state transition to RunState.failed, (5) tmux session cleanup after timeout, (6) resource impact of concurrent 3600s+ sessions. Future refactoring risks silently re-introducing timeout mismatches.\n",
